" height=3D"125" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"545" data-fil=
e-height=3D"363"></a><figcaption>Top part of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Tic-tac-toe" title=3D"Tic-tac-toe">Tic-tac-toe</a> game tree</fi=
gcaption></figure>
<p><b>Breadth-first search</b> (<b>BFS</b>) is an <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm" title=3D"Algorithm">algorithm</a> for searching =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">tree</a> data structure for a =
node that satisfies a given property. It starts at the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)#Terminology" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">tree root</a> and explores all nodes at =
the present <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)#=
Terminology" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">depth</a=
> prior to moving on to the nodes at the next depth level. Extra memory, us=
ually a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queue_(data_structure)" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Queue (data structure)">queue</a>, is needed t=
o keep track of the child nodes that were encountered but not yet explored.=
=20
</p><p>For example, in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chess_end=
game" title=3D"Chess endgame">chess endgame</a>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Chess_engine" title=3D"Chess engine">chess engine</a> may =
build the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Game_tree" title=3D"Game=
 tree">game tree</a> from the current position by applying all possible mov=
es and use breadth-first search to find a winning position for White. Impli=
cit trees (such as game trees or other problem-solving trees) may be of inf=
inite size; breadth-first search is guaranteed to find a solution node<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> if one exists.
</p><p>In contrast, (plain) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-=
first_search" title=3D"Depth-first search">depth-first search</a> (DFS), wh=
ich explores the node branch as far as possible before backtracking and exp=
anding other nodes,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
may get lost in an infinite branch and never make it to the solution node. =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterative_deepening_depth-first_se=
arch" title=3D"Iterative deepening depth-first search">Iterative deepening =
depth-first search</a> avoids the latter drawback at the price of exploring=
 the tree's top parts over and over again. On the other hand, both depth-fi=
rst algorithms typically require far less extra memory than breadth-first s=
earch.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Breadth-first search can be generalized to both <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undirected_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Undir=
ected graph">undirected graphs</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Directed_graph" title=3D"Directed graph">directed graphs</a> with a gi=
ven start node (sometimes referred to as a 'search key').<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-f=
irst_search#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/State_space_search" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"State space search=
">state space search</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artifi=
cial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial intelligenc=
e</a>, repeated searches of vertices are often allowed, while in theoretica=
l analysis of algorithms based on breadth-first search, precautions are typ=
ically taken to prevent repetitions.
</p><p>BFS and its application in finding <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Connected_component_(graph_theory)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Connected component (graph theory)">connected components</a> of graphs were=
 invented in 1945 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Konrad_Zuse" =
title=3D"Konrad Zuse">Konrad Zuse</a>, in his (rejected) Ph.D. thesis on th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plankalk%C3%BCl" title=3D"Planka=
lk=C3=BCl">Plankalk=C3=BCl</a> programming language, but this was not publi=
shed until 1972.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-:0-5"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> It was reinvented in 1959 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed=
ward_F._Moore" title=3D"Edward F. Moore">Edward F. Moore</a>, who used it t=
o find the shortest path out of a maze,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_n=
ote-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-skiena_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-skiena-7"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup> and later developed by C. Y. Lee into a <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Routing_(electronic_design_automation)" title=3D"Routing =
(electronic design automation)">wire routing</a> algorithm (published in 19=
61).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Pseudocode">Pseudocode</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBreadth-first_se=
arch&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Pseudocode">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p><b>Input</b>: A graph <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">G</span> and a starting vertex <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">root</span> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">G</span>
</p><p><b>Output</b>: Goal state. The <i>parent</i> links trace the shortes=
t path back to <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">ro=
ot</span><sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<pre> 1  <b>procedure</b> BFS(<i>G</i>, <i>root</i>) <b>is</b>
 2      let <i>Q</i> be a queue
 3      label <i>root</i> as explored
 4      <i>Q</i>.enqueue(<i>root</i>)
 5      <b>while</b> <i>Q</i> is not empty <b>do</b>
 6          <i>v</i>&nbsp;:=3D <i>Q</i>.dequeue()
 7          <b>if</b> <i>v</i> is the goal <b>then</b>
 8              <b>return</b> <i>v</i>
 9          <b>for all</b> edges from <i>v</i> to <i>w</i> <b>in</b> <i>G</=
i>.adjacentEdges(<i>v</i>) <b>do</b>
10              <b>if</b> <i>w</i> is not labeled as explored <b>then</b>
11                  label <i>w</i> as explored
12                  <i>w</i>.parent&nbsp;:=3D <i>v</i>
13                  <i>Q</i>.enqueue(<i>w</i>)
</pre>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"More_details">More details<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBreadth-firs=
t_search&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: More det=
ails"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:MapGermanyGraph.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://=
upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ad/MapGermanyGraph.svg/250px=
-MapGermanyGraph.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"252" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"460" data-file-height=3D"464"><=
/a><figcaption>An example map of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
outhern_Germany" title=3D"Southern Germany">Southern Germany</a> with some =
connections between cities</figcaption></figure>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:GermanyBFS.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uploa=
d.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63/GermanyBFS.svg/250px-GermanyBF=
S.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"179" class=3D"mw-file=
-element" data-file-width=3D"460" data-file-height=3D"330"></a><figcaption>=
The breadth-first tree obtained when running BFS on the given map and start=
ing in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frankfurt" title=3D"Frankfu=
rt">Frankfurt</a></figcaption></figure>
<p>This non-recursive implementation is similar to the non-recursive implem=
entation of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search" ti=
tle=3D"Depth-first search">depth-first search</a>, but differs from it in t=
wo ways:
</p>
<ol><li>it uses a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queue_(abstract_=
data_type)" title=3D"Queue (abstract data type)">queue</a> (<a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_In_First_Out" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"First In First Out">First In First Out</a>) instead of a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stack_(abstract_data_type)" title=3D"Stack (abst=
ract data type)">stack</a> (Last In First Out) and</li>
<li>it checks whether a vertex has been explored before enqueueing the vert=
ex rather than delaying this check until the vertex is dequeued from the qu=
eue.</li></ol>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">G</span> is=
 a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_(data_structure)" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Tree (data structure)">tree</a>, replacing the queue=
 of this breadth-first search algorithm with a stack will yield a depth-fir=
st search algorithm. For general graphs, replacing the stack of the iterati=
ve depth-first search implementation with a queue would also produce a brea=
dth-first search algorithm, although a somewhat nonstandard one.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B=
readth-first_search#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <i>Q</i> queue contains the frontier along which the algorithm i=
s currently searching.
</p><p>Nodes can be labelled as explored by storing them in a set, or by an=
 attribute on each node, depending on the implementation.
</p><p>Note that the word <i>node</i> is usually interchangeable with the w=
ord <i>vertex</i>.
</p><p>The <i>parent</i> attribute of each node is useful for accessing the=
 nodes in a shortest path, for example by backtracking from the destination=
 node up to the starting node, once the BFS has been run, and the predecess=
ors nodes have been set.
</p><p>Breadth-first search produces a <i>breadth-first tree</i> which is s=
hown in the example below.
</p>
