-align: -0.838ex; width:3.081ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle |V|=
}"></span> is the number of vertices. This is in addition to the space
required for the graph itself, which may vary depending on the <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(abstract_data_type)" title=3D"Graph (ab=
stract data type)">graph representation</a> used by an implementation of th=
e algorithm.
</p><p>When working with graphs that are too large to store explicitly (or =
infinite), it is more practical to describe the complexity of breadth-first=
 search in different terms: to find the nodes that are at distance <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">d</span> from the start n=
ode (measured in number of edge traversals), BFS takes <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>O</i>(<i>b</i><sup><i>d</i> + 1</sup>)</span> time and memory, where=
 <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is the =
"<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Branching_factor" title=3D"Branch=
ing factor">branching factor</a>" of the graph (the average out-degree).<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"referenc=
e nowrap"><span title=3D"Page / location: 81">:=E2=80=8A81=E2=80=8A</span><=
/sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Completeness">Completeness<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DBreadth-firs=
t_search&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Complete=
ness"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>In the analysis of algorithms, the input to breadth-first search is assu=
med to be a finite graph, represented as an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Adjacency_list" title=3D"Adjacency list">adjacency list</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix" title=3D"Adjacency m=
atrix">adjacency matrix</a>, or similar representation. However, in the app=
lication of graph traversal methods in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Artificial_intelligence" title=3D"Artificial intelligence">artificial =
intelligence</a> the input may be an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Implicit_graph" title=3D"Implicit graph">implicit representation</a> of =
an infinite graph. In this context, a search method is described as being c=
omplete if it is guaranteed to find a goal state if one exists. Breadth-fir=
st search is complete, but depth-first search is not. When applied to infin=
ite graphs represented implicitly, breadth-first search will eventually fin=
d the goal state, but depth first search may get lost in parts of the graph=
 that have no goal state and never return.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-coppin_13-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_=
search#cite_note-coppin-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
