/span></div>
<p>Breadth-first search can be used to solve many problems in graph theory,=
 for example:
</p>
<ul><li>Copying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Garbage_collection=
_(computer_science)" title=3D"Garbage collection (computer science)">garbag=
e collection</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cheney%27s_algor=
ithm" title=3D"Cheney's algorithm">Cheney's algorithm</a></li>
<li>Finding the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shortest_path" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Shortest path">shortest path</a> between two no=
des <i>u</i> and <i>v</i>, with path length measured by number of edges (an=
 advantage over <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Depth-first_search=
" title=3D"Depth-first search">depth-first search</a>)<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Breadth-fir=
st_search#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuthill%E2%80%93McKee_algorith=
m" title=3D"Cuthill=E2=80=93McKee algorithm">(Reverse) Cuthill=E2=80=93McKe=
e</a> mesh numbering</li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ford%E2%80%93Fulkerson_algorit=
hm" title=3D"Ford=E2=80=93Fulkerson algorithm">Ford=E2=80=93Fulkerson metho=
d</a> for computing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maximum_fl=
ow_problem" title=3D"Maximum flow problem">maximum flow</a> in a <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flow_network" title=3D"Flow network">flow ne=
twork</a></li>
<li>Serialization/Deserialization of a binary tree vs serialization in sort=
ed order, allows the tree to be re-constructed in an efficient manner.</li>
<li>Construction of the <i>failure function</i> of the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aho-Corasick" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Aho-Coras=
ick">Aho-Corasick</a> pattern matcher.</li>
<li>Testing <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bipartite_graph#Testin=
g_bipartiteness" title=3D"Bipartite graph">bipartiteness of a graph</a>.</l=
i>
<li>Implementing parallel algorithms for computing a graph's transitive clo=
sure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Breadth-first_search#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
